# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dál-riata
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dál-riata/1066-and-all-that] Both the Tory view of a 'great man' history, and the liberal pieties of Whig history are undermined in the work, in the (then contemporary) style of such serious historians as Namier and Herbert Butterfield.
[src:dál-riata/1066-and-all-that] With its conflation of history and memory, and its deconstruction of "standard" historical narrative lines, the book can also be seen as an early post-modernist text.
[src:dál-riata/1066-and-all-that] The book is a parody of the style of history teaching in English schools at the time, in particular of *Our Island Story*.
[src:dál-riata/1066-and-all-that] It purports to contain "all the History you can remember", and, in sixty-two chapters, covers the history of England from Roman times through 1066 "and all that", up to the end of World War I, at which time "America was thus clearly Top Nation, and history came to a .".
[src:dál-riata/1066-and-all-that] The book is full of examples of half-remembered and mixed-up facts.
[src:dál-riata/1066-and-all-that] Although the subtitle states that the book comprises "103 Good Things, 5 Bad Kings and 2 Genuine Dates", the book's preface mentions that originally four dates were planned, but last-minute research revealed that two of them were *not memorable*.
[src:dál-riata/1066-and-all-that] The two dates that are referenced in the book are 1066, the date of the Battle of Hastings and the Norman conquest of England (Chapter XI), and 55 BC, the date of the first Roman invasion of Britain under Julius Caesar (Chapter I).
[src:dál-riata/1066-and-all-that] However, when the date of the Roman invasion is given, it is immediately followed by the date that Caesar was "compelled to invade Britain again the following year (54 BC, not 56, owing to the peculiar Roman method of counting)".
[src:dál-riata/1066-and-all-that] Despite the confusion of dates the Roman Conquest is the first of 103 historical events in the book characterised as a *Good Thing*, "since the Britons were only natives at that time".
[src:dál-riata/1066-and-all-that] Chapter II begins "that long succession of Waves of which History is chiefly composed", the first of which, here, is composed of Ostrogoths, Visigoths, mere Goths, Vandals, and Huns.
[src:dál-riata/1066-and-all-that] Later examples are the "Wave of Saints", who include the Venomous Bead (Chapter III); "Waves of Pretenders", usually divided into smaller waves of two: an Old Pretender and a Young Pretender (Chapter XXX); plus the "Wave of Beards" in the Elizabethan era (Chapter XXXIII).
[src:dál-riata/1066-and-all-that] According to Sellar and Yeatman, in English history kings are either "Good" or "Bad".
[src:dál-riata/1066-and-all-that] The first "Good King" is the confusingly differentiated King Arthur/Alfred (Chapter V).
[src:dál-riata/1066-and-all-that] Bad kings include King John, who when he came to the throne showed how much he deserved this epithet when he "lost his temper and flung himself on the floor, foaming at the mouth and biting the rushes" (Chapter XVIII).
[src:dál-riata/1066-and-all-that] Other *memorable* monarchs include the Split King (Henry IV, Part 1 and Henry IV, Part 2) and Broody Mary.
[src:dál-riata/1066-and-all-that] (Protractors may not be used.)" (Test Paper II).
[src:dál-riata/1066-and-all-that] In 1935, the musical comedy *1066 – and all that: A Musical Comedy based on that Memorable History by Sellar and Yeatman* was produced.
[src:dál-riata/1066-and-all-that] The book and lyrics were by Reginald Arkell; the music was composed by Alfred Reynolds.
[src:dál-riata/1066-and-all-that] It was revived at the Palace Theatre, London, in 1945.
[src:dál-riata/1066-and-all-that] Ned Sherrin and Neil Shand wrote a sequel *1956 and All That*, with the subtitle *a memorable history of England since the war to end all wars (Two)*.
[src:dál-riata/1066-and-all-that] In 2005 Craig Brown released *1966 and All That*, which copied the book's style (including elements like the end of chapter tests), recounting the remainder of the 20th century.
[src:dál-riata/1066-and-all-that] In 2006 the book was adapted for BBC Radio 4 in four parts.
[src:dál-riata/1066-and-all-that] Acknowledging the debt, Armour dedicated his book to Sellar and Yeatman.
[src:dál-riata/1066-and-all-that] Dave Barry's 1989 book *Dave Barry Slept Here: A Sort of History of the United States* is another treatment of American history reminiscent of *1066 and All That*, though Sellar and Yeatman are not acknowledged.
[src:dál-riata/1066-and-all-that] Matthew Sturgis' book *1992 and All This* (Macmillan, 1991) is a "humorous look at Europe in preparation for 1992 when Britain officially becomes part of the Continent.
[src:dál-riata/a-history-of-britain-tv-series] A study of the history of the British Isles, each of the 15 episodes allows Schama to examine a particular period and tell of its events in his own style.
[src:dál-riata/a-history-of-britain-tv-series] All the programmes are of 59 minutes' duration and were broadcast over three series, ending 18 June 2002.
[src:dál-riata/a-history-of-britain-tv-series] The series was produced in conjunction with the History Channel and the executive producer was Martin Davidson.
[src:dál-riata/a-history-of-britain-tv-series] The music was composed by John Harle, whose work was augmented by vocal soloists such as Emma Kirkby and Lucie Skeaping.
[src:dál-riata/a-history-of-britain-tv-series] Schama's illustrative presentation was aided by readings from actors, including Lindsay Duncan, Michael Kitchen, Christian Rodska, Samuel West and David Threlfall.
[src:dál-riata/a-history-of-britain-tv-series] When Simon Schama was approached by the BBC to make the series, he knew that it would be a big commitment and took a long time to decide whether it was something he wanted to do.
[src:dál-riata/a-history-of-britain-tv-series] He surmised that if he were to take it on, he would want to "dive in" and be very involved with the production.
[src:dál-riata/a-history-of-britain-tv-series] Besides writing the scripts, which the historian saw as a "screenplay", he also had input into other aspects, including the choice of locations.
[src:dál-riata/a-history-of-britain-tv-series] He was concerned that even 15 hour-long programmes would not be enough to tell a story of such magnitude.
[src:dál-riata/a-history-of-britain-tv-series] Accordingly, he and the producers determined that to give each king and queen absolute equal coverage was out of the question: "That way lies madness," he said.
[src:dál-riata/a-history-of-britain-tv-series] Instead, he worked out the essential themes and stories that demanded to be related.
[src:dál-riata/a-history-of-britain-tv-series] Schama explained why, at the time of its making, it was right to produce another historical documentary on Great Britain.
[src:dál-riata/a-history-of-britain-tv-series] At that moment, he argued, Britain was entering a new phase of its relationship with Europe and the rest of the world, and where it would end up depended a great deal on where it's come from.
[src:dál-riata/a-history-of-britain-tv-series] He stated that the stories needed to be told again and again so that future generations could get a sense of their identity.
[src:dál-riata/a-history-of-britain-tv-series] The main criticism of *A History of Britain* is that it mostly revolves around England and its history, rather than that of Great Britain in its entirety.
[src:dál-riata/a-history-of-britain-tv-series] In a BBC interview, Simon Schama stated that rather than designating different periods of screen time to different nations, he focused on the relationships between the different nations, primarily England and Scotland.
[src:dál-riata/a-history-of-britain-tv-series] By the latter episodes, however, all "Three Kingdoms" are parts of the United Kingdom.
[src:dál-riata/a-history-of-britain-tv-series] The series is available in the UK (Regions 2 and 4) as a six-disc DVD (BBCDVD1127, released 18 November 2002) in widescreen PAL format.
[src:dál-riata/a-history-of-britain-tv-series] Its special features include short interviews with Simon Schama, a text-based biography of the historian, and the inaugural BBC History Lecture of Schama's "Television and the Trouble with History".
[src:dál-riata/a-history-of-britain-tv-series] In Region 1, it was released as *A History of Britain: the complete collection* on 26 November 2002.
[src:dál-riata/a-history-of-britain-tv-series] A five-disc set, the episodes were presented in full-frame NTSC format and included various text-based features.
[src:dál-riata/a-history-of-britain-tv-series] It was re-released on 22 July 2008 in a new slim-case version.
[src:dál-riata/a-history-of-britain-tv-series] It was released again in Region 1 on 17 August 2010 in a format nearly identical to the UK version noted above.
[src:dál-riata/a-history-of-britain-tv-series] Three accompanying books by Simon Schama have been published by BBC Books.
[src:dál-riata/act-for-the-settlement-of-ireland-1652] The **Act for the Settling of Ireland** imposed penalties including death and land confiscation against Irish civilians and combatants after the Irish Rebellion of 1641 and subsequent unrest.
[src:dál-riata/act-for-the-settlement-of-ireland-1652] British historian John Morrill wrote that the act and associated forced movements represented "perhaps the greatest exercise in ethnic cleansing in early modern Europe".
[src:dál-riata/act-for-the-settlement-of-ireland-1652] The act was passed on 12 August 1652 by the Rump Parliament of England, which had taken power after the Second English Civil War and had agreed to the Cromwellian conquest of Ireland.
[src:dál-riata/act-for-the-settlement-of-ireland-1652] The conquest was deemed necessary as Royalist supporters of Charles II of England had allied themselves with the Confederation of Kilkenny (the confederation formed by Irish Catholics during the Irish Confederate Wars) and so were a threat to the newly formed English Commonwealth.
[src:dál-riata/act-for-the-settlement-of-ireland-1652] Also money to pay for the wars had been raised under the 1642 Adventurers' Act, that repaid creditors with land forfeited by the 1641 rebels.
[src:dál-riata/act-for-the-settlement-of-ireland-1652] These and other creditors had mostly resold their property interests to local landowners who wanted these recent property transfers reconfirmed by an over-riding Act, for the avoidance of doubt.
[src:dál-riata/act-for-the-settlement-of-ireland-1652] Ten named leaders of the Royalist forces in Ireland, together with anyone who had participated in the Irish Rebellion's early stages and who had killed an Englishman other than in battle, lost their lives and estates.
[src:dál-riata/act-for-the-settlement-of-ireland-1652] The Act includes a list of a 104 men who were excluded from pardon for life and estate.
[src:dál-riata/act-for-the-settlement-of-ireland-1652] This list includes members of the nobility, the landed gentry, army officers, and clergy.
[src:dál-riata/act-for-the-settlement-of-ireland-1652] It includes royalists as well as supporters of the Confederation.
[src:dál-riata/act-for-the-settlement-of-ireland-1652] Richard Butler, 3rd Viscount Mountgarret.
[src:dál-riata/act-for-the-settlement-of-ireland-1652] The Act made a distinction between the rebels of 1641 – who were deemed unlawful combatants – as against those who had fought in the regular armies of Confederate Ireland, who were treated as legitimate combatants provided that they had surrendered before the end of 1652.
[src:dál-riata/act-for-the-settlement-of-ireland-1652] The 1641 rebels and the above-mentioned Royalist leaders were excluded from the pardon given to soldiers who had surrendered: they were to be executed when captured.
[src:dál-riata/act-for-the-settlement-of-ireland-1652] Roman Catholic clergy were also excluded from the pardon, as the Cromwellians held them responsible for fomenting the Irish Rebellion of 1641.
[src:dál-riata/act-for-the-settlement-of-ireland-1652] The remaining leaders of the Irish army lost the vast majority of their estates, causing Catholic land ownership to fall to just 8% across the island.
[src:dál-riata/act-for-the-settlement-of-ireland-1652] To have been merely a bystander was itself a crime, and anyone who had resided in Ireland any time from 1 October 1649, to 1 March 1650 and had not "manifested their constant good affection to the interest of the Commonwealth of England" lost three-quarters of their land.
[src:dál-riata/act-for-the-settlement-of-ireland-1652] This was interpreted by the English Parliamentarian authorities in Ireland who ordered all Irish land owners to leave for those lands before 1 May 1654 or be executed.
[src:dál-riata/act-for-the-settlement-of-ireland-1652] However, in practice, most Catholic landowners stayed on their land as tenants and the numbers of those either transplanted or executed was small.
[src:dál-riata/act-for-the-settlement-of-ireland-1652] Protestant Royalists, on the other hand, could avoid land confiscations if they had surrendered by May 1650 and had paid fines to the Parliamentarian government.
[src:dál-riata/act-for-the-settlement-of-ireland-1652] The Commonwealth initially had harsh plans to remove the formerly-Scottish Presbyterians from north-east Ulster – as they had fought with the Royalists in the later stages of the war.
[src:dál-riata/act-for-the-settlement-of-ireland-1652] However, this was reversed in 1654, and it was ruled that the plantation would apply to Catholics only.
[src:dál-riata/act-for-the-settlement-of-ireland-1652] In Irish popular memory of the Cromwellian Plantation, the Commonwealth is said to have declared that all the Catholic Irish must go "to Hell or to Connaught", west of the River Shannon.
[src:dál-riata/act-for-the-settlement-of-ireland-1652] However, according to historian Padraig Lenihan, "The Cromwellians did not proclaim 'To Hell or to Connaught'.
[src:dál-riata/act-for-the-settlement-of-ireland-1652] Connaught was chosen as a native reservation not because the land was poor; The Commonwealth rated Connaught above Ulster in this respect".
[src:dál-riata/act-for-the-settlement-of-ireland-1652] Lenihan suggests that County Clare was chosen instead for security reasons – to keep Catholic landowners penned between the sea and the river Shannon.
[src:dál-riata/act-for-the-settlement-of-ireland-1652] The Cromwellian transplantation, particularly in Ulster, is often cited as an early modern example of ethnic cleansing.
[src:dál-riata/act-for-the-settlement-of-ireland-1652] Some Irish prisoners were forcibly sent on ships to the West Indies where they became indentured servants on sugar cane plantations belonging to British colonialists.
[src:dál-riata/act-for-the-settlement-of-ireland-1652] One of the best known islands the Irish flocked to when their period of indenture came to an end was Montserrat.
[src:dál-riata/act-for-the-settlement-of-ireland-1652] The reality was that a landowner and his family might be dispossessed and awarded land in Connacht, and be obliged to live there, generally as a tenant farmer.
[src:dál-riata/act-for-the-settlement-of-ireland-1652] An example was Thomas FitzGerald of Turlough, whose parents were moved from Gorteens Castle to land granted in Turlough, County Mayo.
[src:dál-riata/act-for-the-settlement-of-ireland-1652] The vast majority of the population, outside the 6 counties that would later be partitioned into Northern Ireland, were expected to remain where they lived, and to continue as tenant farmers or servants under the new freeholders.
[src:dál-riata/act-for-the-settlement-of-ireland-1652] In the next of the Plantations of Ireland, the confiscated land was granted to the "Adventurers".
[src:dál-riata/act-for-the-settlement-of-ireland-1652] The new owners were known as "planters".
[src:dál-riata/act-for-the-settlement-of-ireland-1652] The Adventurers were financiers who had loaned the Parliament £10 million in 1642, specifically to reverse the 1641 rebellion, and the Act had been signed into law by Charles I just before the start of the Wars of the Three Kingdoms (see Adventurers' Act 1640).
[src:dál-riata/act-for-the-settlement-of-ireland-1652] Many of Ireland's pre-war Protestant inhabitants also took advantage of the confiscation of Catholic-owned land to increase their own holdings, buying land off the Adventurers.
[src:dál-riata/act-for-the-settlement-of-ireland-1652] In addition, smaller grants of land were given to 12,000 veterans of the New Model Army who had served in Ireland, much of which was also resold.
[src:dál-riata/act-for-the-settlement-of-ireland-1652] Decisions on confiscations and awards were based on mapping and data in the Down Survey made in 1655–56.
[src:dál-riata/act-for-the-settlement-of-ireland-1652] In June 1657, the Act of Settlement 1657 "for the Assuring, Confirming and Settling of lands and estates in Ireland" ratified previous decrees, judgments, grants and instructions made or given by the various officers and councils in applying the 1652 Act.
[src:dál-riata/act-for-the-settlement-of-ireland-1652] All Ordinances and Acts of Parliament passed during the English Civil War and the Interregnum were considered void after the English Restoration as they had not received Royal assent.
[src:dál-riata/act-for-the-settlement-of-ireland-1652] In 1662, an Act of Settlement 1662 (after the Restoration) aimed to reduce its effect on Protestant and "innocent Catholics".
[src:dál-riata/act-for-the-settlement-of-ireland-1652] This Act returned some lands to prominent Irish Royalists, but left most of the land confiscated from Irish Catholics in Protestant hands.
[src:dál-riata/adomnán] Adomnán promulgated the Law of Adomnán or "Law of Innocents" (Latin: *Lex Innocentium*).
[src:dál-riata/adomnán] He also wrote the treatise *De Locis Sanctis* ('On Holy Places'), an account of the great Christian holy places and centres of pilgrimage.
[src:dál-riata/adomnán] Adomnán got much of his information from a Frankish bishop called Arculf, who had personally visited Egypt, Rome, Constantinople and the Holy Land, and visited Iona afterwards.
[src:dál-riata/adomnán] Adomnán was born about 624, a relative on his father's side of Columba.
[src:dál-riata/adomnán] He was a member of the Northern Uí Néill lineage Cenél Conaill.
[src:dál-riata/adomnán] He was the son of Rónán mac Tinne by Ronat, a woman from another Northern Uí Néill lineage known as the Cenél nÉnda.
[src:dál-riata/adomnán] Adomnán's birthplace was probably in or near Raphoe, a town in what later became Tír Chonaill (now mainly County Donegal), in Ulster in the north of Ireland.
[src:dál-riata/adomnán] Some of Adomnán's childhood anecdotes seem to confirm at least an upbringing in this fertile eastern part of present-day County Donegal, not far from the modern city of Derry.
[src:dál-riata/adomnán] It is thought that Adomnán may have begun his monastic career at a Columban monastery called Druim Tuamma, but any Columban foundation in northern Ireland or Dál Riata is a possibility, although Durrow is a stronger possibility than most.
[src:dál-riata/adomnán] He probably joined the Columban *familia* (i.e. the federation of monasteries under the leadership of Iona Abbey) around 640.
[src:dál-riata/adomnán] Some modern commentators believe that he could not have come to Iona until sometime after 669, the year of the accession of Fáilbe mac Pípáin, the first abbot of whom Adomnán gives any information.
[src:dál-riata/adomnán] However, Richard Sharpe argues that he probably came to Iona during the abbacy of Ségéne (d.
[src:dál-riata/adomnán] Whenever or wherever Adomnán received his education, Adomnán attained a level of learning rare in early-medieval Northern Europe.
[src:dál-riata/adomnán] It has been suggested by Alfred Smyth that Adomnán spent some years teaching and studying at Durrow, and while this is not accepted by all scholars, it remains a strong possibility.
[src:dál-riata/adomnán] In 679, Adomnán became the ninth abbot of Iona after Columba.
[src:dál-riata/adomnán] Abbot Adomnán enjoyed a friendship with King Aldfrith of Northumbria.
[src:dál-riata/adomnán] In 684, Aldfrith stayed with Adomnán in Iona.
[src:dál-riata/adomnán] Adomnán, in keeping with Ionan tradition, made several more trips to the lands of the English during his abbacy, including one the following year.
[src:dál-riata/adomnán] It is sometimes thought, after the account given by Bede, that it was during his visits to Northumbria, under the influence of Abbot Ceolfrith, that Adomnán decided to adopt the Roman dating of Easter that had been agreed some years before at the Synod of Whitby.
[src:dál-riata/adomnán] Bede implies that this led to a schism at Iona, whereby Adomnán became alienated from the Iona brethren and went to Ireland to convince the Irish of the Roman dating.
[src:dál-riata/adomnán] Jeffrey Wetherill sees Adomnán's long absences from Iona as having led to something of an undermining of his authority; he was thus unable to persuade the monks to adopt the Roman dating of Easter, let alone the tonsure.
[src:dál-riata/adomnán] It is clear that Adomnán did adopt that Roman dating and, moreover, probably did argue the case for it in Ireland.
[src:dál-riata/adomnán] For many years, the people of Leinster made a triennial tribute payment, called the *Borumha*, to the Uí Néill.
[src:dál-riata/adomnán] Around 692, the King of Leinster was prepared to go to war over the payment, but first sent a delegation led by Saint Moling to ask for its remittance.
[src:dál-riata/adomnán] Fínsnechta Fledach agreed to remit payment "for a day and a night".
[src:dál-riata/adomnán] Moling argued that "All time is day and night; thou canst never reimpose this tax." Although this was not the king's intention, Moling held him to his word, promising him heaven if he kept it, and the reverse if he did not.
[src:dál-riata/adomnán] When Adomnán learned of this he left Iona to see the king and scolded him soundly for yielding the rights of the Uí Néill.
[src:dál-riata/adomnán] It is generally believed that in 697, Adomnán promulgated the *Cáin Adomnáin*, meaning literally the "Canons" or "Law of Adomnán".
[src:dál-riata/adomnán] The *Cáin Adomnáin* was promulgated amongst a gathering of Irish, Dál Riatan and Pictish notables at the Synod of Birr in 697.
[src:dál-riata/adomnán] It is a set of laws designed, among other things, to guarantee the safety and immunity of various types of non-combatants in warfare.
[src:dál-riata/adomnán] For this reason it is also known as the *Lex Innocentium* (Law of Innocents).
[src:dál-riata/adomnán] Adomnán's most important work, and the one for which he is best known, is the *Vita Columbae* ("Life of Columba"), a hagiography of Iona's founder, Columba, probably written between 697 and 700.
[src:dál-riata/adomnán] The format borrows to some extent from Sulpicius Severus' *Life of Saint Martin of Tours*.
[src:dál-riata/adomnán] Adomnán adapted traditional forms of Christian biography to group stories about Columba thematically rather than chronologically, and present Columba as comparable to a hero in Gaelic mythology.
[src:dál-riata/adomnán] Wetherill suggests that one of the motivations for writing the *Vita* was to offer Columba as a model for the monks, and thereby improve Adomnán's standing as abbot.
[src:dál-riata/adomnán] The biography is by far the most important surviving work written in early-medieval Scotland, and is a vital source for our knowledge of the Picts, as well as a great insight into the life of Iona and the early-medieval Gaelic monk.
[src:dál-riata/adomnán] However, the *Vita* was not his only work.
[src:dál-riata/adomnán] Adomnán also wrote the treatise *De Locis Sanctis* (i.e.
[src:dál-riata/adomnán] "On Holy Places"), an account of the great Christian holy places and centres of pilgrimage.
[src:dál-riata/adomnán] Adomnán got much of his information from a Frankish bishop called Arculf, who had personally visited the Egypt, Rome, Constantinople and the Holy Land, and visited Iona afterwards.
[src:dál-riata/adomnán] Adomnán gave a copy to the scholar-king Aldfrith of Northumbria (685–704).
[src:dál-riata/adomnán] Also attributed to him is a good deal of Gaelic poetry, including a celebration of the Pictish King Bridei's (671–93) victory over the Northumbrians at the Battle of Dun Nechtain (685).
[src:dál-riata/adomnán] Adomnán died in 704, and became a saint in Scottish and Irish tradition, as well as one of the most important figures in either Scottish or Irish history.
[src:dál-riata/adomnán] His death and feast day are commemorated on 23 September.
[src:dál-riata/adomnán] Along with Columba, he is joint patron of the Roman Catholic Diocese of Raphoe, which encompasses the bulk of County Donegal in the north-west of Ireland.
[src:dál-riata/adomnán] The Cathedral of St Eunan and St Columba (popularly known as St.
[src:dál-riata/adomnán] Eunan's Cathedral), the Catholic cathedral in that diocese, is in Letterkenny.
[src:dál-riata/adomnán] In 727 the relics of Adomnán were brought to Ireland to renew the *Cáin Adomnáin* and they were returned to Iona in 730.
[src:dál-riata/adomnán] In County Sligo, just to the south, he is venerated as the founder of Skreen Abbey, now the site of the Church of Ireland church of Skreen Parish.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] The **Aedui** or **Haedui** (Gaulish: **Aiduoi*, 'the Ardent') were a Gallic people dwelling in central-eastern Gaul, in the country between the Loire and the Saône (modern Burgundy), during the Iron Age and the Roman period.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] From the middle of the 2nd century BC they were allies of Rome, the first people of inner Gaul to conclude a formal treaty (*foedus*) with the Republic and, according to Tacitus, the only Gauls to bear the title *fratres populi Romani* ('brothers of the Roman people').
[src:dál-riata/aedui] During the Gallic Wars (58–50 BC) they gave Caesar important if uneven support before briefly joining the revolt of Vercingetorix in 52 BC.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] Their aristocracy was thereafter rapidly integrated into the Roman order, and under Claudius in 48 AD they were the first Gauls admitted to the Roman Senate.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] Their principal *oppidum*, Bibracte on Mont Beuvray, was replaced under Augustus by a new capital, Augustodunum (Autun).
[src:dál-riata/aedui] They are mentioned as *Haedui* by Cicero (mid-1st c.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] AD), *Aidúōn* (Αἰδύων) by Ptolemy (2nd c.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] AD), and as *Aídouoi* (Aἴδουοι) by Cassius Dio (3rd c.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] The ethnonym *Aedui* is a Latinized form of Gaulish **Aiduoi* (sing.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] It derives from the Celtic stem **aidu-* ('fire, ardour', cf.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] Old Irish *áed* 'fire', Welsh *aidd* 'ardour'), itself from Proto-Indo-European: **h₂eydʰos* ('firewood', cf.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] Sanskrit *édhas* 'bonfire', Latin *aedes* 'building, temple').
[src:dál-riata/aedui] The Aedui held a central position in eastern Gaul, on the watershed dividing the Mediterranean, Atlantic and Channel drainage basins.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] Their territory was bounded on the west by the Loire (*Liger*), which separated them from the Bituriges, and on the east by the Saône (*Arar*), which separated them from the Sequani.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] To the south lay their clients the Segusiavi and the first foothills of the Massif Central, held by the Arverni, and to the north the edge of the Morvan and the country of their clients the Mandubii.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] The river ports of *Cabillonum* (Chalon-sur-Saône) and *Matisco* (Mâcon) controlled the traffic of the Saône.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] The Saône did not, however, form a stable linear frontier.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] The river was easily forded and presented no real obstacle.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] The boundary between Aedui and Sequani was sinuous rather than parallel to its course, with Aeduan enclaves on the eastern bank (notably around Chalon and Verdun) and Sequanian holdings to the west.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] A weakly occupied zone south of Chalon, on the Bresse side, seems to have formed a kind of march separating the two peoples.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] Three oppida are known from the end of the La Tène period: Vieux-Dun (Dun-les-Places), Le Fou de Verdun (Lavault-de-Frétoy), and Bibracte, which occupied a central position in the Aedian economic system.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] Bibracte, the principal *oppidum* of the Aedui, occupied an isolated hill of the Morvan (Mont Beuvray, culminating at 820 m) at the meeting point of the basins of the Yonne, the Loire, the Seine and the Saône.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] Occupied and probably fortified since the Neolithic, it reached its height in the 1st century BC before being progressively abandoned towards the end of that century in favour of Augustodunum.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] The interior was hierarchically arranged, with sanctuaries on the highest points, aristocratic residences and the market on the plateau.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] The craft quarters were located lower down, near the gates and in the outer suburb between the two lines of rampart.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] Augustodunum's earliest urban occupation barely predates the turn of the era.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] Only a small and unevenly distributed part of the urban area, of the order of one per cent, has been excavated down to the earliest levels as of 2015, so that the picture of the Julio-Claudian town remains very incomplete.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] Before the Roman conquest the Aedui were one of the major political and military powers of central Gaul, contending for a preeminence with their powerful neighbours, the Sequani, Bituriges and Arverni.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] Their *civitas* was an oligarchy in which the conduct of affairs lay with a senate, an assembly probably made up of the representatives of the great families, which had replaced the older assembly of the people in arms, convened only in exceptional cases such as a declaration of war.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] Current business and the administration of justice lay with an annual magistrate, the *vergobret*, elected for one year, probably by the senate.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] The names of several holders are known: Dumnorix (ca.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] 60 BC), Liscos (58 BC), Valetiacos (53 BC), and Cotos, whose contested election in 52 BC was settled by Caesar in favour of his rival Convictolitavis.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] A law forbade the supreme magistrate to leave the territory of the *civitas*.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] The farming of taxes and tolls was let by auction.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] The Aedui concluded an alliance with Rome at an undetermined moment around 150–140 BC.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] With the Remi they were the traditional allies of Rome in Gaul, and according to Livy they were already allied with the Republic before 121 BC, when Domitius Ahenobarbus invoked the alliance in order to campaign against the Allobroges.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] They were the first people of inner Gaul to contract such an alliance and, according to Tacitus, the only Gauls to bear the title *fratres populi Romani*.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] This title was granted at the moment the *foedus* was concluded and reconfirmed by successive decrees of the Senate.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] The treaty was a *foedus aequum*, an equal treaty resting on reciprocal *fides* between two peoples whose territories were not contiguous.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] It entailed mutual military assistance together with the right of hospitality (*hospitalitas*).
[src:dál-riata/aedui] Caesar called the Aedui consanguineous brothers (*fratres consanguinei*).
[src:dál-riata/aedui] The alliance brought lasting Roman influence, as shown by a silver coinage aligned on the denarius and the early introduction of Roman-style architecture at Bibracte, a site that Olivier Buchsenschutz has described as a bridgehead of Roman influence towards the north of Gaul.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] In 61 BC the Aeduan noble Diviciacus appealed to the Roman Senate for help against the Sequani, Arverni and Germani, but in vain.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] Diviciacus, brother of Dumnorix and a partisan of Rome, had been received at Rome by Cicero, who records that he was a Druid.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] He became Caesar's trusted intermediary.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] When the Helvetii resolved to migrate to the country of the Santones across Aeduan territory, the *foedus* served Caesar as a pretext to intervene in the still unconquered part of Gauls (*Gallia comata*).
[src:dál-riata/aedui] At the Aedui's request Caesar intervened in 58 BC against the Germani of Ariovistus, then allied with the Sequani within an Arvernian coalition.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] Diviciacus guided the Roman legions into Alsace for the decisive battle.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] His brother Dumnorix led the anti-Roman faction.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] As son-in-law of the Helvetian Orgetorix, he had held the supreme magistracy shortly before 58 BC and had farmed the Aeduan tolls and taxes for several consecutive years.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] His wealth allowed him to maintain a body of cavalry as a personal guard, and he commanded the Aeduan cavalry furnished to Caesar.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] His collusion with the Helvetii was treated as treason, and he was spared only through his brother's influence.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] In 54 BC, at *Portus Itius* (Boulogne), he refused to embark for Britain and was killed in flight, crying that he was a free man belonging to a free people.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] During the war the Aedui were divided, supporting the Romans most of the time but also the insurgents during the brief revolt of 52 BC.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] After Caesar's final victory they kept their laws and their title of *fratres populi Romani*.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] As allies, the Aedui were not conquered but received Roman citizenship directly.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] Their capital was transferred from Bibracte to a new town, Augustodunum (Autun), created *ex nihilo* on the order of Augustus at the end of the 1st century BC.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] It lay about twenty kilometres west of Bibracte, on the road laid out under Agrippa.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] From its creation the city was enclosed by a wall some 6 kilometres long delimiting nearly 200 hectares, a privilege normally reserved for Latin or Roman colonies.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] It took the name of its founder: Augustodunum ('the town of Augustus'), from the Gaulish suffix *-dunum* ('town, fortress').
[src:dál-riata/aedui] The legal status of the city is disputed.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] Pliny lists it among the federated communities (*civitates foederatae*), but Antony Hostein, treating Pliny's testimony with caution, argues that the *civitas* held the status of a Latin-right colony from early on, perhaps from its foundation.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] Excavation suggests that the move was a gradual shift rather than a sudden abandonment: the public buildings and craft quarters were transferred first in the last decade BC.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] The aristocratic habitat moved later, only a sparse occupation remaining on the old *oppidum* after about 15 BC.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] Under Claudius, a delegation of Gallic notables (the *primores Galliae*, designated by the council of the Ara Romae at Lyon) petitioned the emperor and the Senate in 48 AD for the right to pursue a senatorial career at Rome.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] Claudius supported the request, but the Senate granted access not to the notables of all Three Gauls but to the Aedui alone as old allies The Aedui thus became the first Gauls to obtain the right to sit in the Roman Senate.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] In 269–270 AD, Augustodunum was besieged for seven months and sacked.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] The city had declared for the legitimate emperor Claudius II, the Aedui being the first to solicit his help to recover the Gauls against the Gallic emperor Victorinus.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] Defended by its population, the city fell when the relief it awaited failed to arrive.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] The repression that followed included the proscription of the city's notables and the confiscation of their property.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] The city was restored under the Tetrarchy and Constantine, and in 312 it was renamed *Flavia Aeduorum* in honour of Constantine.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] The only Druid named among the Aedui is Diviciacus, whom Cicero received at Rome and recorded as a member of the order.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] At Augustodunum, inscriptions attest the cult of the goddess Bibracte, who bears the name of the former *oppidum*, of Anvallos, and the presence of a temple of Apollo.
[src:dál-riata/aedui] The Temple of Janus, probably erected second half of the 1st century AD, was located just outside Augustodunum.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In the period 1150 to 1300, warm dry summers and less severe winters allowed cultivation at much greater heights and made land more productive.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Arable farming grew significantly, but was still more common in low-lying areas than in high-lying areas such as the Highlands, Galloway and the Southern Uplands.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The system of infield and outfield agriculture, a variation of open-field farming widely used across Europe, may have been introduced with feudalism from the twelfth century.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Crops were bere (a form of barley), oats and sometimes wheat, rye and legumes.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Hunting reserves were adopted by Anglo-Norman lords and then by Gaelic ones.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The more extensive outfield was used for oats.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] New monastic orders such as the Cistercians became major landholders and sheep farmers, particularly in the Borders where they were organised in granges.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] By the late Medieval period, most farming was based on the Lowland fermtoun or Highland baile, settlements of a handful of families that jointly farmed an area notionally suitable for two or three plough teams, allocated in run rigs to tenant farmers, known as husbandmen.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Runrigs usually ran downhill so that they included both wet and dry land.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Most ploughing was done with a heavy wooden plough with an iron coulter, pulled by oxen, which were more effective and cheaper to feed than horses.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Sheep and goats were probably the main sources of milk, while cattle were raised for meat.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The rural economy appears to have boomed in the thirteenth century and in the immediate aftermath of the Black Death was still buoyant, but by the 1360s there was a severe falling off in incomes to be followed by a slow recovery in the fifteenth century.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Scotland is roughly half the size of England and Wales and has approximately the same amount of coastline, but only between a fifth and a sixth of the amount of the arable or good pastoral land, under 60 metres above sea level, and most of this is located in the south and east.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] This made marginal pastoral farming and fishing, the key factors in the pre-modern economy.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Its east Atlantic position means that it has moderate rainfall: today about 700 mm per year in the east and over 1,000 mm in the west.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] This encouraged the spread of blanket peat bog, the acidity of which, combined with high level of wind and salt spray, made most of the western islands treeless.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The existence of hills, mountains, quicksands and marshes made agriculture and internal communication difficult.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The early Middle Ages, from the fifth century to the tenth century, were a period of climate deterioration, with a drop in temperature and an increase in rainfall, resulting in more land becoming unproductive.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] With a lack of significant transport links and wider markets, most farms had to produce a self-sufficient diet of meat, dairy products and cereals, supplemented by hunter-gathering.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The climate meant that more oats and barley were grown than wheat.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The evidence of bones indicates that cattle were by far the most important domesticated animal, followed by pigs, sheep and goats, while domesticated fowl were very rare.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Christian missionaries from Ireland may have changed agricultural practice, bringing innovations such as the horizontal watermill and mould board ploughs, which were more effective in turning the soil.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In the period 1150 to 1300, warm dry summers and less severe winters of the Medieval Warm Period allowed cultivation at much greater heights above sea level and made land more productive.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Arable farming grew significantly, but was still more common in low-lying areas in the south and east than in high-lying areas such as the Highlands, Galloway and the Southern Uplands.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The feudalism introduced under David I, particularly in the east and south where the crown's authority was greatest, saw the placement of baronial lordships.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Land was now held from the king, or a superior lord, in exchange for loyalty and forms of service that were usually military.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Barons, who held feudal tenures, had the right to hold baronial courts, which could deal with matters of land ownership.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] However, the imposition of feudalism continued to sit beside the existing systems of landholding and tenure and it is not clear how this change impacted on the lives of the ordinary free and unfree workers.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In places, feudalism may have tied workers more closely to the land.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] However, the predominantly pastoral nature of Scottish agriculture may have made the imposition of a manorial system, based on the English model, impracticable in some areas.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Obligations appear to have been limited to occasional labour service, seasonal renders of food, hospitality and money rents.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They usually included supplying oxen for ploughing the lord's land on an annual basis and the much resented obligation to grind corn at the lord's mill.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Hunting reserves were adopted by Anglo-Norman lords and then by Gaelic ones, creating large tracts of land reserved for the leisure of the aristocracy and nobility.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] These were less rigorously enforced than in England, where the taking of wood and game were strictly forbidden, and all royal forests were on land already in the king's hands.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The introduction of new monastic orders such as the Cistercians in this period also brought innovations in agriculture.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Particularly in the Borders, their monasteries became major landholders, sheep farmers and producers of wool for the markets in Flanders.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] These were organised in granges, monastic farms run by lay brothers of the order.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Granges were theoretically within 30 miles of the mother monastery, so that those working there could return for services on Sundays and feast days.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They were used for variety of purposes, including pastoral, arable and industrial production.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] However, to manage more distant assets in Ayrshire, Melrose Abbey used Mauchline as a "super grange", to oversee lesser granges.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Some abbeys like Melrose had at least 12,000 sheep in the late thirteenth century.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The system of infield and outfield agriculture, a variation of open field farming widely used across Europe, may have been introduced with feudalism and would continue until the eighteenth century.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] This expanded from the use of small enclosed fields, which continued from the prehistoric era.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The infield was the best land, close to housing.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] It was farmed continuously and most intensively, receiving most of the manure.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Crops were usually bere (a form of barley), oats and sometimes wheat, rye and legumes.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The more extensive outfield was used for largely for oats.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] It was fertilised from the overnight folding of cattle in the summer and was often left fallow to recover its fertility.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In fertile regions the infield could be extensive, but in the uplands it might be small, surrounded by large amounts of outfield.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In coastal areas fertiliser included seaweed and around the major burghs urban refuse was used.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Yields were fairly low, often around three times the quantity of seed sown, although they could reach twice that yield on some infields.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The main unit of land measurement in Scotland was the *davoch* (i.e.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] This unit is also known as the "Scottish ploughgate".
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In English-speaking Lothian, it was simply a ploughgate.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] It may have measured about 104 acres (0.42 km2), divided into 4 *raths* or eight *oxgangs*, the area that eight oxen were said to be able to plough in one year.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] By the fourteenth century most farming was based on the Lowland fermtoun or Highland baile, settlements of a handful of families that jointly farmed an area notionally suitable for two or three plough teams.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] These were allocated in run rigs to tenant farmers, who were usually known as husbandmen or bonders.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The average amount of land used by a husbandman in Scotland, known as a husbandland, was 26 acres, or 2 oxgangs.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They would also have had a share of hay meadow and common pasture.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Below the husbandmen, lesser landholders and free tenants, were the cottars, who often shared rights to common pasture, occupied small portions of land and participated in joint farming as hired labour.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Farms also might have grassmen, who had rights only to grazing.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Pasture was often accessed by shieling-grounds, with shelters made of stone or turf, used for the grazing of cattle in summer.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] These would often be distant from the main settlements in the Lowlands, but might be relatively close in the more remote Highlands.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Runrigs, were a ridge and furrow pattern, similar to that used in parts of England, with alternating "runs" (furrows) and "rigs" (ridges).
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They usually ran downhill so that they included both wet and dry land, helping to offset some of the problems of extreme weather conditions.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Most ploughing was done with a heavy wooden plough with an iron coulter, pulled by oxen, which were more effective on heavy soils and cheaper to feed than horses.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They were usually pulled by a team of eight oxen, which would have taken four men to operate and only covered half an acre a day.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Key crops included kale (for both humans and animals), and hemp and flax for cloth production.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Sheep and goats were probably the main sources of milk, while cattle were raised primarily for meat.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] This was followed by a slow recovery in the fifteenth century.
[src:dál-riata/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Towards the end of the period average temperatures began to reduce again, with the cooler and wetter conditions of the Little Ice Age limiting the extent of arable agriculture, particularly in the Highlands.
[src:dál-riata/ahenny] Ahenny is situated close to the border dividing counties Tipperary and Kilkenny and nestles on the slopes of Carrigadoon Hill overlooking the valley of the river Lingaun.
[src:dál-riata/ahenny] Scattered remnants of a once thriving slate industry spanning the Tipperary-Kilkenny border-lands, act as reminders of modern Ahenny's roots.
[src:dál-riata/ahenny] A number of megalithic tombs dot the landscape surrounding Ahenny, which was located in the ancient Kingdom of Ossory.
[src:dál-riata/ahenny] Two kilometres east on Killmacoliver Hill is the Baunfree megalithic tomb, while two kilometres north, the passage tomb of Knockroe (the Coshel) sits on a hill summit.
[src:dál-riata/ahenny] The Knockroe passage tomb shares similarities with Newgrange, Knowth and Loughcrew and is one of the most decorated tombs outside of the Boyne valley group.
[src:dál-riata/ahenny] Ten kilometres to the west is Slievenamon Hill, again with a Neolithic summit cairn.
[src:dál-riata/ahenny] The river Lingaun rises on Slievenamon and flows east for some ten kilometres before turning south to flow through a valley between Carrigadoon and Kilmacoliver hills.
[src:dál-riata/ahenny] This bend occurs some six kilometres north of Ahenny and it marks the boundary of Leinster from Munster, and the boundary between County Tipperary and County Kilkenny.
[src:dál-riata/ahenny] It also lies at the intersection of three ecclesiastic dioceses: Ossory, Waterford and Cashel.
[src:dál-riata/ahenny] The Ossory group of high crosses are amongst the earliest (8th/9th century) examples of Celtic high crosses to be found in Ireland, with those in west Ossory considered the oldest.
[src:dál-riata/ahenny] The west Ossory group of Celtic crosses includes Ahenny and Kilkieran – two kilometres south-east., Eight kilometres further south is Tibberaghny.
[src:dál-riata/ahenny] Killamery High Cross eight kilometres north of Ahenny completes this close group: although Kilree High Cross sixteen miles north-east of Ahenny is often included.
[src:dál-riata/ahenny] The Ahenny high crosses (national monument #124) are early examples of Irish high crosses which still bear resemblance to their wooden predecessors.
[src:dál-riata/ahenny] Celtic knotwork and bosses imitate in stone what a carved wooden cross would have looked like.
[src:dál-riata/ahenny] One of the Ahenny crosses also bears a fine image of an Irish chariot, which along with other high crosses, was used as the main inspiration of a modern reconstruction.
[src:dál-riata/ahenny] Nearby in County Kilkenny are the Kilkieran High Crosses.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] In Argyll, it consisted of four main kindreds or tribes, each with their own chief: the Cenél nGabráin (based in Kintyre), the Cenél nÓengusa (based on Islay), the Cenél Loairn (who gave their name to the district of Lorn) and the Cenél Comgaill (who gave their name to Cowal).
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] The hillfort of Dunadd is believed to have been its capital.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Other royal forts included Dunollie, Dunaverty and Dunseverick.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Within Dál Riata was the important monastery of Iona, which played a key role in the spread of Celtic Christianity throughout northern Britain, and in the development of insular art.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Iona was a centre of learning and produced many important manuscripts.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Dál Riata had a strong seafaring culture and a large naval fleet.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Dál Riata is said to have been founded by the legendary king Fergus Mór (Fergus the Great) in the 5th century.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] The kingdom reached its height under Áedán mac Gabráin (r.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] During his reign Dál Riata's power and influence grew; it carried out naval expeditions to Orkney and the Isle of Man, and assaults on the Brittonic kingdom of Strathclyde and Anglian kingdom of Bernicia.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] However, King Æthelfrith of Bernicia checked its growth at the Battle of Degsastan in 603.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Serious defeats in Ireland and Scotland during the reign of Domnall Brecc (died 642) ended Dál Riata's "golden age", and the kingdom became a client of Northumbria for a time.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] In the 730s the Pictish king Óengus I led campaigns against Dál Riata and brought it under Pictish overlordship by 741.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] There is disagreement over the fate of the kingdom from the late 8th century onwards.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Some scholars have seen no revival of Dál Riatan power after the long period of foreign domination (c.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] 750–760), while others have seen a revival under Áed Find (736–778).
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Some even claim that the Dál Riata usurped the kingship of Fortriu.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] From 795 onward there were sporadic Viking raids in Dál Riata.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] In the following century, there may have been a merger of the Dál Riatan and Pictish crowns.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Some sources say Cináed mac Ailpín (Kenneth MacAlpin) was king of Dál Riata before becoming king of the Picts in 843, following a disastrous defeat of the Picts by Vikings.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] The kingdom's independence ended sometime after, as it merged with Pictland to form the Kingdom of Alba.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Latin sources often referred to the inhabitants of Dál Riata as *Scots* (*Scoti*), a name originally used by Roman and Greek writers for the Irish Gaels who raided and colonised Roman Britain.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Later, it came to refer to Gaels, whether from Ireland or elsewhere.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] They are referred to herein as *Gaels* or as *Dál Riatans*.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] The name **Dál Riata** comes from Old Irish and means "the portion of Riata".
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] *Dál* is part of the names of other Irish territories, such as Dál Fiatach and Dál gCais.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] *Riata* is the genitive of a tribal name or deity name.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Bede wrote that the kingdom was named after its founder, a man called Reuda.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Some Old Gaelic texts say that the kingdom was named after the Corcu Réti, descendants of Domangart Réti.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Another legend says that it was named after one Cairbre Riata.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] The Dalradian geological series, a term coined by Archibald Geikie in 1891, was named after Dál Riata because its outcrop has a similar geographical reach to that of the former kingdom.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Dál Riata spanned the North Channel and included parts of western Scotland and north-eastern Ireland.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] In Scotland, it corresponded roughly to Argyll (from *Airer Goídel*, "coast of the Gaels") and later grew to include Skye.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] In Ireland, it took in the north-east of County Antrim, roughly corresponding to the baronies of Cary and Glenarm.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] The modern human landscape of Dál Riata differs a great deal from that of the first millennium.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Most people today live in settlements far larger than anything known in early times, while some areas, such as Kilmartin, and many of the islands, such as Islay and Tiree, may well have had as many inhabitants as they do today.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Many of the small settlements have now disappeared so that the countryside is far emptier than was formerly the case, and many areas that were formerly farmed are now abandoned.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] As was normal at the time, subsistence farming was the occupation of most people.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Oats and barley were the main cereal crops.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Pastoralism was especially important, and transhumance (the seasonal movement of people with their livestock between fixed summer and winter pastures) was the practice in many places.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Some areas, most notably Islay, were especially fertile, and good grazing would have been available all year round, just as it was in Ireland.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Tiree was famed in later times for its oats and barley, while smaller, uninhabited islands were used to keep sheep.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] The area, until lately, was notable for its inshore fisheries, and for plentiful shellfish, therefore seafood is likely to have been an important part of the diet.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] The Senchus does not list any kindreds in Ireland, but does list an apparently very minor kindred called Cenél Chonchride in Islay descended from another son of Erc, Fergus Becc.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Another kindred, Cenél Báetáin of Morvern (later Clan MacInnes), branched off from Cenél Loairn about the same time that Cenél Comgaill separated from its parent kindred.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] The Morvern district was formerly known as Kinelvadon, after the Cenél Báetáin.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] The Cenél Loairn may have been the largest of the "three kindreds", as the Senchus reports it being divided further into Cenél Shalaig, Cenél Cathbath, Cenél nEchdach, Cenél Murerdaig.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Among the Cenél Loairn it also lists the Airgíalla, although whether this should be understood as being Irish settlers or simply another tribe to whom the label was applied is unclear.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Bannerman proposes a tie to the Uí Macc Uais.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] The meaning of Airgíalla 'hostage givers' adds to the uncertainty, although it must be observed that only one grouping in Ireland was apparently given this name and it is therefore very rare, perhaps supporting the Ui Macc Uais hypothesis.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] There is no reason to suppose that this is a complete or accurate list.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Four sites in Dál Riata may have had royal associations: Dunadd, Dunollie, Dunaverty and Tarbert.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Among them, Dunadd appears to have been the most important.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] It has been partly excavated, and weapons, quern-stones and many moulds for the manufacture of jewellery were found in addition to fortifications.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Other high-status materials included glassware and wine amphorae from Gaul, and in larger quantities than found elsewhere in Britain and Ireland.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Lesser centres included Dun Ollaigh, seat of the Cenél Loairn kings, and Dunaverty, at the southern end of Kintyre, in the lands of the Cenél nGabráin.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] The main royal centre in Ireland appears to have been at Dunseverick (*Dún Sebuirge*).
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Dál Riata had a strong seafaring culture, which was tribal and piratic.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] It was an archipelago with many islands and peninsulas.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] This, and the difficulty of overland travel, meant that travel by sea was the easiest means of moving any distance.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] As well as long-distance trade, local trade must also have been significant.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Currachs were probably the most common seagoing craft, and on inland waters dugouts and coracles were used.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Large timber ships, called "long ships", perhaps similar to the Viking ships of the same name, are attested to in a variety of sources.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Dál Riata had a large war fleet manned by skilled sailors, capable of undertaking far-reaching expeditions.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] It had an organised system for manning the fleet.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Houses were grouped into twenties for the purpose of naval recruitment, with each group having to provide a quota of 28 oarsmen.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] No written accounts exist for pre-Christian Dál Riata, and the earliest-known records come from the chroniclers of Iona and Irish monasteries.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] During the time of Saint Patrick, Dál Riatan kings thought they were descended from Celtic gods, and pagans in the region viewed certain springs and "spirit-inhabited groves of trees" as sacred groves.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Adomnán's *Life of St Columba* implies a Christian Dál Riata.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] The figure of Columba looms large in any history of Christianity in Dál Riata.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Adomnán's *Life*, although useful as a record, was not intended to serve as history, but rather as hagiography.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Because the writing of the lives of the saints in Adomnán's day had not reached the stylised formulas of the High Middle Ages, the *Life* contains a great deal of historically valuable information.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] It is also a vital linguistic source indicating the distribution of Gaelic and P-Celtic placenames in northern Scotland by the end of the 7th century.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] It famously notes Columba's need for a translator when conversing with an individual on Skye.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] This evidence of a non-Gaelic language is supported by a sprinkling of P-Celtic placenames on the remote mainland opposite the island.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Columba's founding Iona within the bounds of Dál Riata ensured that the kingdom would be of great importance in the spread of Christianity in northern Britain, not only to Pictland, but also to Northumbria, via Lindisfarne, to Mercia, and beyond.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Although the monastery of Iona belonged to the Cenél Conaill of the Northern Uí Néill, and not to Dál Riata, it had close ties to the Cenél nGabráin, ties which may make the annals less than entirely impartial.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] If Iona was the greatest religious centre in Dál Riata, it was far from unique.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Lismore, in the territory of the Cenél Loairn, was sufficiently important for the death of its abbots to be recorded with some frequency.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Applecross, probably in Pictish territory for most of the period, and Kingarth on Bute are also known to have been monastic sites, and many smaller sites, such as on Eigg and Tiree, are known from the annals.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] In Ireland, Armoy was the main ecclesiastical centre in early times, associated with Saint Patrick and with Saint Olcán, said to have been the first bishop at Armoy.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] An important early centre, Armoy later declined, overshadowed by the monasteries at Movilla (Newtownards) and Bangor.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] As well as their primary spiritual importance, the political significance of religious centres cannot be dismissed.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] The prestige of being associated with the saintly founder was of no small importance.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Monasteries represented a source of wealth as well as prestige.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Additionally, the learning and literacy found in monasteries served as useful tools for ambitious kings.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] The illuminated manuscript Book of Kells was probably at least begun at Iona, although not by Columba as legend has it, as it dates from about 800.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] (It may have been commissioned to mark the bicentennial of Columba's death in 597).
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Whether it was or not, Iona was certainly important in the formation of Insular art, which combined Mediterranean, Anglo-Saxon, Celtic and Pictish elements into a style of which the book of Kells is a late example.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] For other arts, a number of sculptures remain to give an impression of Dál Riatan work.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Martin's Cross on Iona is the well-preserved high cross, probably inspired by Northumbrian free-standing crosses, such as the Ruthwell Cross, although a similar cross exists in Ireland (Ahenny, County Tipperary).
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] The Kildalton Cross on Islay is similar.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] A sculpted slab at Ardchattan appears to show strong Pictish influences, while the Dupplin Cross, it has been argued, shows that influences also moved in the opposite direction.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Fine Hiberno-Saxon metalwork such as penannular brooches is believed to have been created at Dunadd.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] In addition to the monastic sites, a considerable number of churches are attested, not only from archaeological evidence, but also from the evidence of place names.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] The element "kil", from Gaelic *cill*, can be shown in many cases to be associated with early churches, such as at Kilmartin by Dunadd.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] The 11th-century *Duan Albanach* (Song of the Scots) tells that the three sons of Erc—Fergus Mór, Loarn and Óengus—conquered *Alba* (Scotland) in around 500.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] The 8th-century writer Bede offers another, and probably older, account wherein Dál Riata was conquered by Irish Gaels led by a certain *Reuda*.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Old Irish *dál* means 'portion' or 'share', and is usually followed by the name of an eponymous founder.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Bede's tale may come from the same root as the Irish tales of Cairpre Riata and his brothers, the Síl Conairi (sons/descendants of Conaire Cóem and Conaire Mór).
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] The story of Dál Riata moves from foundation myth to something nearer to history with the reports of the death of Comgall mac Domangairt around 540 and of his brother Gabrán around 560.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] The version of history in the *Duan Albanach* was long accepted, although it is preceded by the fictional tale of Albanus and Brutus conquering Britain.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Traditionally, the presence of Gaelic in Scotland has been seen as the result of either a migration from Ireland, or a takeover by Irish Gaelic elites.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] However, in his academic paper *Were the Scots Irish?*, archaeologist Dr Ewan Campbell says that there is no archaeological or placename evidence of a migration or takeover.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] This lack of archaeological evidence was previously noted by Professor Leslie Alcock.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Campbell suggests that Argyll and Antrim formed a "maritime province", united by the sea and isolated from the rest of Scotland by the mountains of the Highlands, historically called the *Druim Alban*.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] This hypothetical separation allowed a shared language to be maintained through the centuries; Argyll remained Gaelic-speaking while the rest of Scotland spoke either Pictish or another Brittonic language.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Campbell suggests that the medieval accounts were a kind of dynastic propaganda, constructed to bolster a dynasty's claim to the throne and to bolster Dál Riata claims to territory in Antrim.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Although this view of the medieval accounts is shared by other historians, his theory has been challenged.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Irish scholar Eoin MacNeill postulated that Scottish Dál Riata came about in two stages.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] He conjectured that Irish settlements were founded in Argyll at the time of Irish raids on Britain, during the end of Roman rule.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Later, as these settlements became economically and politically more significant than the home territory, its rulers moved from Ireland to Argyll.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] The time in which Dál Riata arose was one of great instability in Ulster, following the Ulaid's loss of territory (including the ancient centre of Emain Macha) to the Airgíalla and the Uí Néill.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] 47–50, notes a later conquest of Irish Dál Riata from Scotland, in the period after the fall of Emain Macha.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Linguistic and genealogical evidence associates ancestors of the Dál Riata with the prehistoric Iverni and Darini, suggesting kinship with the Ulaid and a number of shadowy kingdoms in distant Munster.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] The Robogdii have also been suggested as ancestral.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Ultimately, the Dál Riata, according to the earliest genealogies, are descendants of Deda mac Sin, a prehistoric king or deity of the Érainn.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] By the mid-6th century, the Dál Riata in Scotland came under serious threat from Bridei I, king of the Picts, whilst the Irish portion faced hostility from the Dál nAraidi of Ulaid, resulting in their seeking the aid of the Irish Northern Uí Néill.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Dál Riata reached its greatest extent in the reign of Áedán mac Gabráin, who was said to have been consecrated by Columba, to whom Áedán granted the island of Iona off the coast of Scotland.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Columba, who was also a Cenél Conaill prince, negotiated an alliance between Dál Riata and the Cenél Conaill, who were the ruling dynasty of the Northern Uí Néill, in 575 at the Convention of Druim Cett near Limavady.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] In attendance were Columba, Áedán mac Gabráin, and Áed mac Ainmuirech, king of the Northern Uí Néill and High King of Ireland.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] What is certain is that both parties had the Dál nAraidi as a common foe.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] 603. Æthelfrith's brother was among the dead, but Áedán was defeated, and the Bernician kings continued their advances in southern Scotland. Áedán died c.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Dál Riata did expand to include Skye, possibly conquered by Áedán's son Gartnait.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] It has been suggested that Fiachnae mac Báetáin (died 626), Dál nAraidi over-king of Ulaid, was overlord of both parts of Dál Riata.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Fiachnae campaigned against the Northumbrians, and besieged Bamburgh, and the Dál Riatans are thought to have fought in this campaign.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] In 629, the Dál Riata suffered significant losses at the battle of Fid Euin where the Dál nAraidi, led by Congal Cáech mac Scandláin, killed the Dál Riata king as well as three grandsons of Áedán mac Gabráin.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] It is suggested to have been an achievement that Dál Riata itself survived this battle.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] That same year the Cenél Conaill defeated Congal Cáech at the battle of Dún Ceithirn.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Dál Riata remained allied with the Northern Uí Néill until the reign of Domnall Brecc, who was persuaded by the king of Dál nAraidi, Congal Cáech, to renounce this alliance.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] A battle had also taken place at sea at Sailtír, off Kintyre, in 637.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] This defeat was then attributed as divine retribution for Domnall Brecc turning his back on his prior alliance.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Domnall Brecc's policy appears to have died with him in 642, at his final, and fatal, defeat by Eugein map Beli of Strathclyde at Strathcarron, for as late as the 730s, armies and fleets from Dál Riata fought alongside the Uí Néill.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] This defeat shattered the power of Dál Riata as well as that of Dál nAraidi, allowing the Northern Uí Néill to become the dominant force in the north of Ireland.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] By the 10th century, the Irish lands of Dál Riata were under the control of the Uí Tuirtri, and their clients, the Fir Lí.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] It has been proposed that some of the more obscure kings of Dál Riata mentioned in the Annals of Ulster, such as Fiannamail ua Dúnchado and Donncoirce, may have been kings of Irish Dál Riata.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] The after-effect of the Battle of Moira (Mag Rath) in regards to Scottish Dál Riata appears to have resulted in its becoming tributary to Northumbrian kings, which lasted until the Pictish king Bruide mac Bili defeated Ecgfrith of Northumbria at Dun Nechtain in 685.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] It is not certain that this subjection ended in 685, although this is usually assumed to be the case.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] However, it appears that Eadberht Eating made some effort to stop the Picts under Óengus mac Fergusa crushing Dál Riata in 740.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Whether this means that the tributary relationship had not ended in 685, or if Eadberht sought only to prevent the growth of Pictish power, is unclear.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Since it has been thought that Dál Riata swallowed Pictland to create the Kingdom of Alba, the later history of Dál Riata has tended to be seen as a prelude to future triumphs.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] The annals make it clear that the Cenél Gabraín lost any earlier monopoly of royal power in the late 7th century and in the 8th, when Cenél Loairn kings such as Ferchar Fota, his son Selbach, and grandsons Dúngal and Muiredach are found contesting for the kingship of Dál Riata.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] The long period of instability in Dál Riata was only ended by the conquest of the kingdom by Óengus mac Fergusa, king of the Picts, in the 730s.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] After the third campaign by Óengus in 741, Dál Riata then disappears from the Irish records for a generation.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Áed Find may appear in 768, fighting against the Pictish king of Fortriu.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] At his death in 778, Áed Find is called "king of Dál Riata", as is his brother Fergus mac Echdach in 781.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] The Annals of Ulster say that a certain Donncoirche, "king of Dál Riata" died in 792, and there the record ends.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Any number of theories have been advanced to fill the missing generations, none of which are founded on any very solid evidence.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] A number of kings are named in the *Duan Albanach*, and in royal genealogies, but these are rather less reliable than we might wish.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] The obvious conclusion is that whoever ruled the petty kingdom of Dál Riata after its defeat and conquest in the 730s, only Áed Find and his brother Fergus drew the least attention of the chroniclers in Iona and Ireland.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] This argues very strongly for Alex Woolf's conclusion that Óengus mac Fergusa "effectively destroyed the kingdom".
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] It is unlikely that Dál Riata was ruled directly by Pictish kings, but it is argued that Domnall, son of Caustantín mac Fergusa, was king of Dál Riata from 811 to 835.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] He was apparently followed by the last named king of Dál Riata Áed mac Boanta, who was killed in the great Pictish defeat of 839 at the hands of the Vikings.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] In the 9th century, the Picts were becoming Gaelicised, and it is suggested that there was a merger of the Dál Riatan and Pictish kingships.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Traditionally, this is attributed to Cináed mac Ailpín (Kenneth MacAlpin), who became king of the Picts in about 843.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Some sources say that Cináed was king of Dál Riata for two years before this.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] Under the House of Alpin, Dál Riata and Pictland merged to form the Kingdom of Alba or Scotland.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] If the Vikings had a great impact on Pictland and in Ireland, in Dál Riata, as in Northumbria, they appear to have entirely replaced the existing kingdom with a new entity.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] In the case of Dál Riata, this was to be known as the kingdom of the Sudreys, traditionally founded by Ketill Flatnose (*Caitill Find* in Gaelic) in the middle of the 9th century.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] The Frankish *Annales Bertiniani* may record the conquest of the Inner Hebrides, the seaward part of Dál Riata, by Vikings in 847.
[src:dál-riata/dál-riata] In turn, Woolf suggests that this gave rise to the terms *Airer Gaedel* and *Innse Gall*, respectively, "the coast of the Gaels" and the "Islands of the foreigners".
